04909nam a22006255i 9780271074283DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710742837 a10.1515/97802710742832doi  a(DE-B1597)584130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0300002bisacsh04a615.5072/409748111 aHornblum, Allen M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSentenced to Science :bOne Black Man's Story of Imprisonment in America /cAllen M. Hornblum. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b16 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- t1 "My Back Is on Fire" -- t2 "The Jungle" -- t3 "Bubble-Eyed Butch" -- t4 "Don't Serve Time; Let Time Serve You" -- t5 "He's Got a Body Like Marilyn Monroe" -- t6 "They Called Me Outer Limits" -- t7 "Fruit Up" -- t8 "He Still Has the Cork in His Ass!" -- t9 "Those Doctors Ain't Interested in You" -- t10 "I Tried My Best" -- t11 "I Was in Some Deep Shit Now" -- t12 "My Spiritual Awakening" -- t13 "It Was a Jihad" -- t14 "Feeling Death Blow Past My Face" -- t15 "A Righteous Life" -- t16 "Trying to Get a Little Justice" -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1951 until 1974, Holmesburg Prison in Philadelphia was the site of thousands of experiments on prisoners conducted by researchers under the direction of University of Pennsylvania dermatologist Albert M. Kligman. While most of the experiments were testing cosmetics, detergents, and deodorants, the trials also included scores of Phase I drug trials, inoculations of radioactive isotopes, and applications of dioxin in addition to mind-control experiments for the Army and CIA. These experiments often left the subject-prisoners, mostly African Americans, in excruciating pain and had long-term debilitating effects on their health. This is one among many episodes of the sordid history of medical experimentation on the black population of the United States.The story of the Holmesburg trials was documented by Allen Hornblum in his 1998 book Acres of Skin. The more general history of African Americans as human guinea pigs has most recently been told by Harriet Washington in her 2007 book Medical Apartheid. The subject is currently a topic of heated public debate in the wake of a 2006 report from an influential panel of medical experts recommending that the federal government loosen the regulations in place since the 1970s that have limited the testing of pharmaceuticals on prison inmates.Sentenced to Science retells the story of the Holmesburg experiments more dramatically through the eyes of one black man, Edward "Butch" Anthony, who suffered greatly from the experiments for which he "volunteered" during multiple terms at the prison. This is not only one black man's highly personal account of what it was like to be an imprisoned test subject, but also a sobering reminder that there were many African Americans caught in the viselike grip of a scientific research community willing to bend any code of ethics in order to accomplish its goals and a criminal justice system that sold prisoners to the highest bidder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Penology.2bisacsh1 aWashington, Harriet.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271074283zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271074283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271074283/original  